00:11:26.940 --> 00:11:29.280
I'm like, what should
we call it Agent force,

00:11:30.420 --> 00:11:32.340
Whether or not a name
change is in order,

00:11:32.340 --> 00:11:35.250
it's clear that agents
are the talk of the tower.

00:11:35.250 --> 00:11:38.160
But how far will this whole
agent thing actually go?

00:11:38.160 --> 00:11:40.920
Alright, go agents.

00:11:40.920 --> 00:11:44.130
Seriously how far

00:11:45.120 --> 00:11:47.550
Salesforce's revenue
has reliably grown year

00:11:47.550 --> 00:11:48.870
over year from the start.

00:11:48.870 --> 00:11:50.850
But for the coming year,
they gave a forecast

00:11:50.850 --> 00:11:53.680
that fell short of estimates,
sparking pessimism.

00:11:53.680 --> 00:11:57.100
So all eyes are on Benioff's
AI strategy, what it means

00:11:57.100 --> 00:11:58.780
for the future of Salesforce,

00:11:58.780 --> 00:12:00.970
and even the human workforce too.

00:12:00.970 --> 00:12:04.810
So you've said you won't hire
any more coders at Salesforce,

00:12:04.810 --> 00:12:08.290
and you've said today's
CEOs will be the last

00:12:08.290 --> 00:12:11.020
to manage all human workforces.

00:12:11.020 --> 00:12:13.360
What does this mean for businesses?

00:12:13.360 --> 00:12:15.250
Well, I think I just
had a meeting, you know,

00:12:15.250 --> 00:12:17.530
coming from a meeting with
my head of engineering,

00:12:17.530 --> 00:12:20.110
and we're looking at
productivity levels of 30

00:12:20.110 --> 00:12:25.110
to 50% this year in key
functions like engineering,

00:12:25.210 --> 00:12:26.530
coding, support.

00:12:26.530 --> 00:12:27.640
You're saying
Service

00:12:27.640 --> 00:12:30.280
AI is doing 30 to 50% of the work.

00:12:30.280 --> 00:12:34.060
AI is doing 30 to 50% of
the work at Salesforce now.

00:12:34.060 --> 00:12:37.960
And I think that that
will, you know, continue.

00:12:37.960 --> 00:12:40.060
I think that this is, we have
to get our, all of us have

00:12:40.060 --> 00:12:44.140
to get our head around this
idea that AI can do things that

00:12:44.140 --> 00:12:46.660
before, you know, we were doing

00:12:46.660 --> 00:12:48.670
and we can move on to
do higher value work.

00:12:50.140 --> 00:12:51.850
Salesforce has cut more than a thousand

00:12:51.850 --> 00:12:53.950
roles already this year.

00:12:53.950 --> 00:12:55.390
While some of these employees might be

00:12:55.390 --> 00:12:57.070
redeployed in new positions.

00:12:57.070 --> 00:12:59.170
These kinds of big reductions are sweeping

00:12:59.170 --> 00:13:01.780
through businesses as
AI takes center stage,

00:13:03.040 --> 00:13:06.280
Salesforce's marketing, its
AI tools on their ability

00:13:06.280 --> 00:13:07.720
to replace human labor.

00:13:07.720 --> 00:13:10.270
Do you have any ethical qualms about that?

00:13:10.270 --> 00:13:14.020
Well, it's a digital labor
revolution that is, you know,

00:13:14.020 --> 00:13:16.900
we're probably looking
at three to $12 trillion

00:13:16.900 --> 00:13:19.510
of digital labor getting deployed.

00:13:19.510 --> 00:13:21.910
And that digital labor's
gonna be everything from AI

00:13:21.910 --> 00:13:23.740
agents to robots.

00:13:23.740 --> 00:13:26.560
And I do think, you know, to
your point, you know, CEOs have

00:13:26.560 --> 00:13:28.780
to make sure their values
are in the right place

00:13:28.780 --> 00:13:30.250
and that values bring value.

00:13:30.250 --> 00:13:32.140
Could an agent replace you one day?

00:13:32.140 --> 00:13:34.090
I hope so.
You hope so?

00:13:34.090 --> 00:13:35.710
I mean, of course I'm partially kidding.

00:13:35.710 --> 00:13:38.500
You know that, but we're
becoming more automated.

00:13:38.500 --> 00:13:39.760
How secure is all this?

00:13:39.760 --> 00:13:41.980
I mean, you know, there's malicious code,

00:13:41.980 --> 00:13:43.240
there's hallucinations.

00:13:43.240 --> 00:13:45.190
Like what are the risks for businesses

00:13:45.190 --> 00:13:46.190
Security,

00:13:46.190 --> 00:13:47.470
You know, there's no finish line.

00:13:47.470 --> 00:13:49.720
You can never have extreme
confidence on security.

00:13:49.720 --> 00:13:51.520
You have to be completely paranoid.

00:13:51.520 --> 00:13:54.280
Hallucinations is a, is a different story.

00:13:54.280 --> 00:13:56.230
The current state of the art

00:13:56.230 --> 00:13:58.540
of AI is not a hundred percent accurate.

00:13:58.540 --> 00:13:59.740
Doesn't it get messier?

00:13:59.740 --> 00:14:01.690
It, it could get a lot more accurate

00:14:01.690 --> 00:14:05.050
because the models themselves are stacking

00:14:05.050 --> 00:14:06.700
their intelligence.

00:14:06.700 --> 00:14:09.970
So hopefully they're
honing what the truth is.

00:14:09.970 --> 00:14:12.100
And I mean, that's the hope.

00:14:12.100 --> 00:14:13.990
But right now it's not a
hundred percent accurate.

00:14:13.990 --> 00:14:17.620
In our own work, we're
doing hundreds of thousands

00:14:17.620 --> 00:14:19.720
of conversations, just our ourself

00:14:19.720 --> 00:14:21.880
and our company with our customers.

00:14:21.880 --> 00:14:24.250
And we have about 93% accuracy.

00:14:24.250 --> 00:14:25.630
Even for a large brand

00:14:25.630 --> 00:14:27.880
or a large company that
we work with, like Disney,

00:14:27.880 --> 00:14:30.370
it's about 93%. It's
not a hundred percent.

00:14:30.370 --> 00:14:33.640
Right. 93% though, that's
not good enough, is it?

00:14:33.640 --> 00:14:34.780
It's pretty good.

00:14:34.780 --> 00:14:36.340
You're able to do a lot,

00:14:36.340 --> 00:14:39.160
but you have to be realistic
that we're not at a hundred.

00:14:39.160 --> 00:14:41.830
You'll never see me saying that
we're at a hundred percent,

00:14:41.830 --> 00:14:44.350
but I think for a lot
of the other vendors,

00:14:44.350 --> 00:14:46.180
maybe they're at much lower levels

00:14:46.180 --> 00:14:49.600
because they don't have
as much data and metadata

00:14:49.600 --> 00:14:50.770
and they're not able to kind of put

00:14:50.770 --> 00:14:52.820
as information into the model to get

00:14:52.820 --> 00:14:54.920
to a higher level of accuracy.

00:14:54.920 --> 00:14:56.990
- That air of competition is at the heart

00:14:56.990 --> 00:14:59.330
of this AI enterprise software game.

00:14:59.330 --> 00:15:02.210
You've been throwing some
shade at Microsoft lately.

00:15:02.210 --> 00:15:05.300
We all know now that Microsoft
copilot is basically the

00:15:05.300 --> 00:15:06.680
new Microsoft Clippy.

00:15:06.680 --> 00:15:09.140
Everyone knows that at
Microsoft has disappointed

00:15:09.140 --> 00:15:11.000
the world with copilot. And I mean that's

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:12.680
Just a, that's just a
repackaged chat g pt, you know

00:15:12.680 --> 00:15:14.300
that? Yeah. Thank you.

00:15:14.300 --> 00:15:18.020
- Marc, - What's the beef?
What did Clippy ever do to you?

00:15:18.020 --> 00:15:20.690
I think we had to make it
clear the difference between

00:15:20.690 --> 00:15:23.180
what we were saying and
what Microsoft was saying.

00:15:23.180 --> 00:15:25.640
And what Microsoft was saying was, Hey we,

00:15:25.640 --> 00:15:28.340
this is a copilot revolution.

00:15:28.340 --> 00:15:31.760
We're all gonna have this
co-pilot. It's about the co-pilot.

00:15:31.760 --> 00:15:34.310
And then customers were
not connecting with that.

00:15:34.310 --> 00:15:35.750
And then we said, no, look at this.

00:15:35.750 --> 00:15:37.460
This is the agent force vision.

00:15:37.460 --> 00:15:39.590
This is what AI was meant to be.

00:15:39.590 --> 00:15:42.170
That these are agents who are
making you more productive

00:15:42.170 --> 00:15:44.990
or reducing your cost,
making things easier.

00:15:44.990 --> 00:15:46.820
Microsoft did try to
buy you back in the day.

00:15:46.820 --> 00:15:48.680
Does that have anything to do with it?

00:15:48.680 --> 00:15:49.910
Well, I don't think
we're gonna go into that.

00:15:51.290 --> 00:15:52.925
What is it between Salesforce and

00:15:52.925 --> 00:15:53.925
Microsoft?

00:15:53.925 --> 00:15:54.980
Well, I mean, they're
fundamentally competitors, right?

00:15:54.980 --> 00:15:59.330
I mean, Microsoft has a suite
of CRM tools, dynamic 365

00:15:59.330 --> 00:16:02.090
that competes with the Salesforce suite.

00:16:02.090 --> 00:16:03.710
They compete in the cloud.

00:16:03.710 --> 00:16:06.110
Azure from Microsoft competing against

00:16:06.110 --> 00:16:07.850
Salesforce's platform.

00:16:07.850 --> 00:16:11.570
You've got a Slack which
Salesforce bought competing against

00:16:11.570 --> 00:16:12.860
Microsoft teams

00:16:12.860 --> 00:16:16.490
and Microsoft's reputation for
bundling software together.

00:16:16.490 --> 00:16:18.860
But look beyond, I think the basics

00:16:18.860 --> 00:16:21.080
of the competition in the marketplace.

00:16:21.080 --> 00:16:25.460
Marc is always someone who
has known the motivating power

00:16:25.460 --> 00:16:26.570
of a rivalry.

00:16:26.570 --> 00:16:28.430
And he learned that
from Larry Ellison, one

00:16:28.430 --> 00:16:29.540
of his first rivals.

00:16:29.540 --> 00:16:30.950
And so I, I think it's something

00:16:30.950 --> 00:16:32.540
that he really loves to talk about.

00:16:32.540 --> 00:16:35.510
This is a market that's probably
big enough for all players,

00:16:35.510 --> 00:16:38.360
but for Mark being able to target the kind

00:16:38.360 --> 00:16:40.670
of evil empire I think is valuable.

00:16:42.230 --> 00:16:45.170
Google and Meta we're on
trial for being monopolies.

00:16:45.170 --> 00:16:47.360
Is big tech too big?
Should it be broken up?

00:16:47.360 --> 00:16:49.280
It probably has been too big

00:16:49.280 --> 00:16:50.630
and it probably should be broken up.

00:16:50.630 --> 00:16:54.500
Especially when you get to ai,

00:16:54.500 --> 00:16:56.780
you're looking at the
amass of even more power.

00:16:56.780 --> 00:16:59.240
So these companies, they
make their own models,

00:16:59.240 --> 00:17:01.070
they control entire industries.

00:17:01.070 --> 00:17:02.990
And for companies that control

00:17:02.990 --> 00:17:06.370
or have monopolistic aspects
of their business, it,

00:17:06.370 --> 00:17:07.520
it has to be looked at.

00:17:07.520 --> 00:17:09.080
And I think that that is a key part

00:17:09.080 --> 00:17:12.500
of the government's role
when it comes to competition.

00:17:12.500 --> 00:17:14.780
And that's definitely one of
the guardrails of capitalism.

00:17:16.010 --> 00:17:17.630
Throughout your career,
you've been an advocate

00:17:17.630 --> 00:17:19.220
for social justice, you've stood up

00:17:19.220 --> 00:17:20.900
for your employees in various states

00:17:20.900 --> 00:17:22.190
through political shifts,

00:17:22.190 --> 00:17:24.320
but more recently you've
stepped back from some

00:17:24.320 --> 00:17:26.240
of the diversity and new
inequality initiatives

00:17:26.240 --> 00:17:27.710
within Salesforce.

00:17:27.710 --> 00:17:29.720
You've been criticized for cheerleading

00:17:29.720 --> 00:17:31.340
for the new administration.

00:17:31.340 --> 00:17:34.400
How do you navigate the
intersection of politics

00:17:34.400 --> 00:17:35.660
and running a global company?

00:17:35.660 --> 00:17:37.130
Yeah, it's two different things.

00:17:37.130 --> 00:17:39.680
And I, you know, I think one thing is

00:17:39.680 --> 00:17:41.780
equality is a core value at Salesforce.

00:17:41.780 --> 00:17:44.270
And as someone who grew
up in San Francisco,

00:17:44.270 --> 00:17:45.800
that's in my heart.

00:17:45.800 --> 00:17:48.650
You know, I guess my
heart has rainbow colors.

00:17:48.650 --> 00:17:52.260
And in terms of making
adjustments at Salesforce, I think

00:17:52.260 --> 00:17:54.840
that, you know, when we can
look at it on, in the reflection

00:17:54.840 --> 00:17:56.520
of the current administration,
what's going on,

00:17:56.520 --> 00:17:58.950
even in the world, you know,
there were certain things

00:17:58.950 --> 00:18:01.440
that we were doing that
just weren't too extreme.

00:18:01.440 --> 00:18:04.050
And so it gave us an
opportunity to look at, hey,

00:18:04.050 --> 00:18:06.240
how do we slightly adjust
what's going on while

00:18:06.240 --> 00:18:08.220
maintaining our core values?

00:18:08.220 --> 00:18:10.380
It's a funny thing, you
know, I own Time Magazine,

00:18:10.380 --> 00:18:11.730
You just interviewed President Trump.

00:18:11.730 --> 00:18:13.530
We have a hundred year history

00:18:13.530 --> 00:18:16.050
that the president who's elected

00:18:16.050 --> 00:18:17.970
that year becomes person of the year.

00:18:17.970 --> 00:18:20.160
Well, if we put him on the cover

00:18:20.160 --> 00:18:22.170
and if we make him person of the year,

00:18:22.170 --> 00:18:25.110
even though it's a hundred
year history at time, we're all

00:18:25.110 --> 00:18:27.240
of a sudden siding with
the administration.

00:18:27.240 --> 00:18:28.830
What I really want Time Magazine

00:18:28.830 --> 00:18:33.150
to be is right down in the
middle and to reflect both sides.

00:18:33.150 --> 00:18:34.830
And I think it's great
that he's on the cover.

00:18:34.830 --> 00:18:36.360
And by the way, lots

00:18:36.360 --> 00:18:39.000
of people are on the
cover. And that's the idea.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:41.430
This is obviously a
cover that, you know,

00:18:41.430 --> 00:18:43.170
there have been people revered

00:18:43.170 --> 00:18:46.350
and despised who have
had that quote unquote,

00:18:46.350 --> 00:18:48.210
honor Benioff got criticized

00:18:48.210 --> 00:18:50.010
for cheerleading President Trump in

00:18:50.010 --> 00:18:51.365
that moment. Is that fair?

00:18:51.365 --> 00:18:54.450
I, I think it's, this is a
moment to be very clear about

00:18:54.450 --> 00:18:56.310
who Marc Benioff is.

00:18:56.310 --> 00:18:58.980
Okay. You know, the things
that he talks about.

00:18:58.980 --> 00:19:02.040
I think these are heartfelt,
but they're also tactics.

00:19:02.040 --> 00:19:03.780
I mean, he's a businessman.

00:19:03.780 --> 00:19:05.400
Salesforce has a lot of business

00:19:05.400 --> 00:19:06.600
with the federal government.

00:19:06.600 --> 00:19:08.700
This is not a president. You
want to be on the enemy's list.

00:19:08.700 --> 00:19:10.830
So I think it was very transactional

00:19:10.830 --> 00:19:13.800
and very much in keeping
with who Marc Benioff is

00:19:13.800 --> 00:19:15.750
and the intelligence that he brings

00:19:15.750 --> 00:19:17.130
to operating in the real world.

00:19:18.270 --> 00:19:20.100
You've had a couple of co-CEOs

00:19:20.100 --> 00:19:21.780
who people thought would replace you.

00:19:21.780 --> 00:19:24.570
It didn't happen. Maybe you
thought they would replace you.

00:19:24.570 --> 00:19:26.130
Why has it been so hard to pass

00:19:26.130 --> 00:19:27.130
the torch?

00:19:27.130 --> 00:19:27.963
It's a good question. I mean,

00:19:27.963 --> 00:19:29.190
maybe you have a good analysis.

00:19:29.190 --> 00:19:31.470
You know, I thought, I've been
on a succession plan several

00:19:31.470 --> 00:19:34.110
times where there was
a successor in place.

00:19:34.110 --> 00:19:36.690
I feel like I always want to
have a successor in place.

00:19:36.690 --> 00:19:38.910
I have one now. I had one before.

00:19:38.910 --> 00:19:40.590
Who is it now?
I've had several before.

00:19:40.590 --> 00:19:42.090
I don't think I should
talk about it anymore.

00:19:42.090 --> 00:19:43.350
Is one of the things I've learned

00:19:43.350 --> 00:19:46.200
because all of a sudden
it like changes maybe

00:19:46.200 --> 00:19:47.490
through nothing I'm doing.

00:19:47.490 --> 00:19:49.050
Or maybe it is something that I'm doing.

00:19:49.050 --> 00:19:50.430
But you can tell me privately

00:19:50.430 --> 00:19:51.755
what you think I, what I should be

00:19:51.755 --> 00:19:52.755
doing.

00:19:52.755 --> 00:19:54.780
Well, so is it them or you?
Why are you sticking around?

00:19:54.780 --> 00:19:57.330
Listen, number one,
I've never been happier,

00:19:57.330 --> 00:19:58.830
more excited about Salesforce.

00:19:58.830 --> 00:20:00.810
You know, I just finished
my management meeting

00:20:00.810 --> 00:20:02.010
and then came right here

00:20:02.010 --> 00:20:04.260
and it went by like a snap, you know,

00:20:04.260 --> 00:20:06.480
because I just am so excited.

00:20:06.480 --> 00:20:09.240
It's like that first minute
that I walked into Radio Shack

00:20:09.240 --> 00:20:11.790
and saw that computer, you know,

00:20:11.790 --> 00:20:13.620
of course you know how life is.

00:20:13.620 --> 00:20:14.850
There's ebbs and flows.

00:20:14.850 --> 00:20:17.910
But right now I'm like,
wow, this is great.

00:20:17.910 --> 00:20:20.130
And it's, it's amazing what's happening.

00:20:20.130 --> 00:20:21.420
I mean, I've never really seen anything.

00:20:21.420 --> 00:20:23.580
I'm sure you see it
yourself everywhere you go.

00:20:23.580 --> 00:20:24.750
Oh yeah. It's an exciting time.

00:20:24.750 --> 00:20:25.770
It's an exciting time.

00:20:25.770 --> 00:20:27.750
It's an incredible moment in our industry.

00:20:30.450 --> 00:20:32.790
You are one of the biggest
philanthropic givers in Hawaii

00:20:32.790 --> 00:20:34.170
and San Francisco,

00:20:34.170 --> 00:20:35.880
and I know you've talked
for many years about

00:20:35.880 --> 00:20:38.130
how more tech leaders need to do that.

00:20:38.130 --> 00:20:40.140
Yeah. What should they
be taking away from the,

00:20:40.140 --> 00:20:41.490
the book of Benioff?

00:20:41.490 --> 00:20:43.860
One thing that's really
powerful is we put 1%

00:20:43.860 --> 00:20:46.260
of our equity, 1% of our profit, 1% of all

00:20:46.260 --> 00:20:48.430
of our employees' time into a foundation.

00:20:48.430 --> 00:20:50.020
25 years ago, it was very easy

00:20:50.020 --> 00:20:52.510
'cause we had no equity,
no profit, no time.

00:20:52.510 --> 00:20:54.700
But we've been able to give
away a billion dollars,

00:20:54.700 --> 00:20:57.670
run a hundred thousand companies
for free on our service.

00:20:57.670 --> 00:21:01.005
Done 10 million hours of
volunteerism. And that's exciting.

00:21:02.050 --> 00:21:05.950
And that is what, you know, an
example that we can give back

00:21:05.950 --> 00:21:07.510
and that business can be the greatest

00:21:07.510 --> 00:21:08.686
platform for change. Yeah,

00:21:08.686 --> 00:21:10.275
That's, but how do you
get other people to do

00:21:10.275 --> 00:21:12.460
It's well, more than 20,000 companies,

00:21:12.460 --> 00:21:14.685
I think now have copied the 1 1 1 model.

00:21:14.685 --> 00:21:16.570
But to become one of the
largest companies in the world

00:21:16.570 --> 00:21:18.760
and to show that you can do well

00:21:18.760 --> 00:21:20.890
and do good, this is our core value.

00:21:20.890 --> 00:21:22.990
And just coming up with
another tech company

00:21:22.990 --> 00:21:25.420
and another product, I was
never interested in that.

00:21:25.420 --> 00:21:29.410
Yeah. - That isn't what
I want to do. Look at this.

00:21:29.410 --> 00:21:31.060
This is gorgeous. Isn't this?

00:21:31.060 --> 00:21:34.330
I mean, you can go all over
the world as we both have.

00:21:34.330 --> 00:21:36.340
You don't have anything quite like this.

00:21:36.340 --> 00:21:37.750
It's just extraordinary.

00:21:37.750 --> 00:21:40.900
You have the top startup in
the world right here, OpenAI.

00:21:40.900 --> 00:21:44.140
You have one of the top hospitals
and medical centers here.

00:21:44.140 --> 00:21:46.510
You've got so many great
things happening in the

00:21:46.510 --> 00:21:47.560
city. It's just a great city.

00:21:47.560 --> 00:21:49.210
Well, so what do you
think about the narrative

00:21:49.210 --> 00:21:51.190
that San Francisco is in decline?

00:21:51.190 --> 00:21:52.840
I think it's a false narrative.

00:21:52.840 --> 00:21:55.450
